---
import DocsNav from "../../components/DocsNav.astro";
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
---
<Layout title="CLI reference">
  <article class="doc">
    <DocsNav active="cli" />
    <h1>CLI reference</h1>
    <p class="intro">Install the native CLI from the <a href="/download">download page</a>, then pass it a file or stdin with a handful of controls.</p>
    <pre>lawlint [options] &lt;file.txt|file.md|file.docx|-&gt;
lawlint init
lawlint learn &lt;path&gt;
lawlint rules --json</pre>
    <div class="table">
      <div><code>--format pretty|json|prompt</code><span>Choose human-readable, machine-readable, or an AI revision brief (<code>prompt</code>) for the flagged text.</span></div>
      <div><code>--rules id,id</code><span>Run only the listed rules.</span></div>
      <div><code>--disable id,id</code><span>Disable selected rules.</span></div>
      <div><code>--markdown</code><span>Strip fenced code blocks from the input. Markdown files enable this automatically.</span></div>
      <div><code>--max-warnings n</code><span>Exit 1 when warnings exceed n.</span></div>
      <div><code>--fix</code><span>Apply machine-applicable fixes in place. For <code>.docx</code>, fixes are written as native Word tracked changes with a review comment per fix.</span></div>
      <div><code>--diff</code><span>Show what <code>--fix</code> would change (or changed) as a colored diff.</span></div>
      <div><code>--judge[=MODEL]</code><span>Run the soft-rule AI judge (the inferential tier). Bare <code>--judge</code> uses the model configured by <code>lawlint init</code>; <code>MODEL</code> overrides it (<code>anthropic:&lt;model&gt;</code>, <code>openai:&lt;base-url&gt;#&lt;model&gt;</code>, <code>foundry:&lt;deployment&gt;</code>, <code>local:&lt;hf-repo&gt;</code>).</span></div>
      <div><code>--rule-dir DIR</code><span>Additional rule package directory (repeatable; merged over built-ins).</span></div>
      <div><code>--quiet</code><span>Suppress pretty output while preserving exit status.</span></div>
      <div><code>init</code><span>Interactive setup: AI model preferences (hosted providers recommended; API keys stored outside the project), judge, Markdown, and custom-rule choices, written to <code>.lawlint/config.json</code>. Supports <code>--yes</code>, <code>--ai MODEL</code>, and <code>--acknowledge-local</code> for non-interactive use.</span></div>
      <div><code>learn PATH</code><span>Mine a personal rule package from a file or directory of your own writing (<code>--out</code> defaults to <code>.lawlint/rules/personal</code>; <code>--model</code> overrides the configured AI model). Generated rules are self-checked so none flags your own prose.</span></div>
      <div><code>rules --json</code><span>Print built-in rule metadata as JSON, including each rule's <code>intent</code> (style or detection).</span></div>
      <div><code>rules test</code><span>Validate rule packages against their flag/pass examples.</span></div>
    </div>
    <h2>Rule kinds</h2>
    <p><strong>Hard rules</strong> are deterministic phrase, leading, density, and statistical checks (static and statistical tiers). <strong>Soft rules</strong> are inferential rules evaluated by the optional AI judge. The JSON API keeps the stable <code>tier</code> values <code>static</code>, <code>statistical</code>, and <code>inferential</code>.</p>
    <h2>Skill-file references</h2>
    <p>Rules are always YAML. An inferential rule can point to a Claude Code-style skill file with <code>skill: ./skills/name/SKILL.md</code>, resolved relative to the YAML file. The skill file's YAML frontmatter and Markdown body provide optional metadata and the rubric. Add at least three bullets under both <code>## Flag examples</code> and <code>## Pass examples</code>, or provide <code>flag_examples</code> and <code>pass_examples</code> arrays in frontmatter. YAML fields take precedence; setting both <code>rubric</code> and <code>skill</code> is invalid. Severity may be warning or suggestion.</p>
    <p><a href="/docs/sdk">Next: SDK reference →</a></p>
  </article>
</Layout>
